Mobilizing woman-power
Contributor: Blatch, Harriot Stanton 1856-1940|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This book by Elizabeth Cady Stanton's daughter emphasizes the importance of women's contributions to World War I. It helps demostrate the link British and American suffragists were making between wartime sacrifice and women's disenfranchisement. There is an interesting foreword by Theodore Roosevelt, which reveals his position on woman suffrage.

Title: Proceedings of the Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women, held in Philadelphia. May 15th, 16th, 17th and 18th, 1838
Contributor: Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women (2d : 1838 : Philadelphia, Pa.)|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This pamphlet helps to emphasize the relationship between abolitionism and women's rights.

Title: From pinafores to politics
Contributor: Harriman, Florence Jaffray 1870-1967|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This autobiography details the life of Daisy Hurst (Mrs. J. Borden) Harriman, a wealthy New York woman who worked diligently for issues concerning working-class women. Harriman was one of the women who lent her financial support to the shirtwaist workers' strike in 1909. In addition, with Mrs. Oliver H.P. Belmont and Miss Anne Morgan, she helped organize a strike meeting of the WTUL at the Colony Club, the first women's social club in New York City, which she also helped organize. In 1912, she was named by Woodrow Wilson to serve on the Federal Industrial Relations Commission.
Topical subject: Women|Political activity|World War, 1914-1918|Politics and government|Social life and customs
Extent: 4 p.l., 359 p. : front., plates (part fold.), ports. ; 24 cm.

Title: The trade union woman
Contributor: Henry, Alice 1857-1943|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: The book examines the history of women's labor organizations and the relationship of working-class women to the campaign for woman suffrage.
Topical subject: Women labor union members|Women in the labor movement|Women|Suffrage
Extent: xxiv p., 1 l., 314 p.  : front., plates ; 20 cm.

Title: Taxation of women in Massachusetts
Contributor: Bowditch, William I. (William Ingersoll) 1819-1909|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|YA Pamphlet Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This pamphlet examines the legal and political status of women in Massachusetts from 1780 to 1871. It includes a brief appendix tabulating the amount women have paid in taxes while being denied the right to vote.
Publisher: Press of John Wilson and Son

Title: Social evils, their causes and cure: being a brief discussion of the social status, with reference to methods of reform
Contributor: King, Maria M.|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: In this pamphlet, the author addresses a number of issues contributing to problems in contemporary society, among them poor diet, prostitution, marriage and divorce, the plight of orphans, and women in prisons. She suggests, in part, that better education for women and their enfranchisement will be a part of the remedy for these social evils.
Publisher: W. White and Company|The American News Company, Agents

Title: Consistent democracy: the elective franchise for women
Contributor: Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: These are very brief (paragraph-length) statements of support for woman suffrage. Among the "prominent men" included are Henry Ward Beecher, William Lloyd Garrison, Horace Greeley, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, Samuel J. May, Theodore Parker, Wendell Phillips, Gerrit Smith, William H. Channing, the Ohio Senate, and the Wisconsin legislature.
Publisher: To be obtained of R.F. Wallcut ...

This pamphlet details the ceremony surrounding this presentation, including speeches by Professor W.C. Larrabee of Indian Asbury University and Robert Dale Owen. What is interesting here is the very narrow way in which the women define their role in society and their prosition vis-a-vis women's rights.

Title: Bible and church degrade woman
Contributor: Stanton, Elizabeth Cady 1815-1902|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: In 1895, Elizabeth Cady Stanton published the first edition of "The Woman's Bible," an attempt to amplify, explain, and redefine scriptural references pertaining to women in the basis that these were often used as a rationale to deny women particular rights and privileges. The work was undertaken by a committee and involved searching the both Old and New Testaments for references to women, cutting them out, and then pasting them on blank pages in a book. Then commentaries were added beneath the quotations. In 1898, "The Woman's Bible" was reprinted, including the addition of a 20-page pamphlet entitled, "Bible and church degrade woman," which contained three essays by Stanton that further explained her position on women in religion. This is one of those essays.

Title: Address before the Second Biennial Convention of the World's Woman's Christian Temperance Union, and the Twentieth Annual Convention of the National Women's Christian Temperance Union
Contributor: Willard, Frances E. (Frances Elizabeth) 1839-1898|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Reprint of a speech delivered at the Art Institute building at the World Columbian Exposition in 1893. Willard was president of both of these organizations. The speech touches on a number of issues concerning women and provides an excellent overview of the relationship between the WCTU and the women's rights campaign.
Name subject: World's Woman's Christian Temperance Union.|Woman's Christian Temperance Union.

Title: Anna Howard Shaw: a memorial
Contributor: National American Woman Suffrage Association|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Shaw was president of NAWSA from 1904-1915. This pamphlet contains several eulogies by unidentified authors.
Publisher: National Women Suffrage Publishing Co., Inc.

Title: Mary S. Gibson, pioneer: memorial, Los Angeles, California, 1930 ; presented by "The Friday Morning Club" to Mrs. Gibson's friends and co-workers, in grateful appreciation
Contributor: Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Mary Simons Gibson was a California teacher, activist, and fund-raiser who supported a large variety of causes. Among these were suffrage for California women, better educational opportunities for women, care of orphaned children, and world peace. This memorial service included eulogies covering various aspects of her life and work

Title: Helen Hamilton Gardener (Alice Chenoweth Day), 1853-1925
Contributor: Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Helen Hamilton Gardener was the pen name of Alice Chenowith Day, a vice-president of NAWSA and the first woman appointed to the U.S. Civil Servive Commission. In "Sex in Brain," she challenged previously held notions that women were intellectually inferior to men on the basis of brain physiology. This memorial service includes eulogies by Carrie Chapman Catt, Maud Wood Park, and her colleagues at the Civil Service Commission.

Title: Life's story
Contributor: Butin, Mary E. Ryerson.|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Butin was a physician, and the first woman to become a member of both the Nebraska State and Fresno County (California) Medical societies. She financed the first suffrage campaign for women in California's San Joaquin Valley. Her autobiography provides a fascinating picture of rural/frontier medicine in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.
Extent: 19 leaves, [3] leaves of plates : 3 ports. ; 29 cm.

Title: Woman and the republic: a survey of the woman-suffrage movement in the United States and a discussion of the claims and arguments of its foremost advocates
Contributor: Johnson, Helen Kendrick 1844-1917|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This book, originally published in 1897, argues against woman suffrage as being antithetical to both democracy and progress. The author maintains that women can progress only in relation to the general progress of humanity. This book was intended to be an answer to the arguments made in the multivolume, "History of Woman Suffrage," published in 1881-1885.
Publisher: Published by The Guidon Club (opposed to woman suffrage)

Title: Debate on woman suffrage in the Senate of the United States, 2d session, 49th Congress, December 8, 1886, and January 25, 1887

Title: Hearing of the National American Woman Suffrage Association, Committee on the Judiciary, House of Representatives, Washington, D.C., January 28, 1896

Title: Report of hearing before the Committee on Woman Suffrage. February 15, 1898
Contributor: United States Congress. Senate. Committee on Woman Suffrage.|Shaw, Anna Howard 1847-1919|United States Congress Senate. (55th, 2nd session : 1897-1898).|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: Woman suffrage and politics: the inner story of the suffrage movement
Contributor: Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|Shuler, Nettie Rogers 1865-1939|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This book addresses the question of why women in twenty-six other countries received the right to vote before American women were enfranchised. The authors blame the liquor lobby for the delay.

Title: A history of the national woman's rights movement, for twenty years: with the proceedings of the decade meeting held at Apollo Hall, October 20, 1870, from 1850 to 1870 ; with an appendix containing the history of the movement during the winter of 1871, in the national capitol
Contributor: Davis, Paulina W. (Paulina Wright) 1813-1876|Woodhull, Victoria C. (Victoria Claflin) 1838-1927|Woodhull, Victoria C. (Victoria Claflin) 1838-1927|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This pamphlet includes speeches by Matilda Joselyn Gage and Elizabeth Cady Stanton, and an appendix including information on actions taken since the convention, including the memorial of Victoria Woodhull to Congress, 19 December 1870, and her "Great Secession" speech before the NAWSA at Apollo Hall, May 11, 1871.

Title: Acquaintances, old and new, among reformers
Contributor: Brown, Olympia 1835-1926|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: An autobiographical account of Olympia Brown's work in the early women's rights movement. It is well-written and easy to read. Its treatment of the events surrounding the early suffrage campaign is a bit superficial but it might provide a good overview for high school students.
Extent: 115 p., [8] leaves of plates : ports. ; 20 cm.

Title: The record of the Leslie Woman Suffrage Commission, Inc., 1917-1929
Contributor: Young, Rose E. (Rose Emmet) 1869-1941|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This is a fascinating account of Miriam Florence Follin Leslie, the wife of Frank Leslie of "Leslie"s Illustrated Newspaper." When Frank Leslie died in 1880, Florence legally changed her name to "Frank Leslie" and continued publishing the paper. When Mrs. Frank died in 1914, she willed $2,000,000 of her estate to Carrie Chapman Catt to be used for the women suffrage campaign. Only $977,000 of that money ever came into Catt's hands. This book by the Leslie Woman Suffrage Commission, which was organized by Catt in 1917, is an account of Mrs. Frank Leslie's life and work and where the rest of the money went.
Name subject: Mrs Leslie, Frank 1836-1914|Leslie Woman Suffrage Commission.
Publisher: The Leslie Woman Suffrage Commission, Inc.

Title: Constitutional equality, a right of woman ; or, A consideration of the various relations which she sustains as a necessary part of the body of society and humanity: with her duties to herself ; together with a review of the Constitution of the United States, showing that the rights to vote is guaranteed to all citizens ; also a review of the rights of children
Contributor: Cook, Tennessee Claflin Lady 1845-1923|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Written by one of the more radical women's rights activists of the nineteenth century and covers a wide range of topics concerning the role of women in American society. It also includes a chapter on the rights of children that focuses on the question of prenatal care.

Title: A lecture on constitutional equality: delivered at Lincoln Hall, Washington, D.C., Thursday, February 16, 1871
Contributor: Woodhull, Victoria C. (Victoria Claflin) 1838-1927|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|Lincoln Music Hall (Washington, D.C.)|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This pamphlet is a continuation of Woodhull's argument on the constitutional enfranchisement of women.

Title: "The Blue book": woman suffrage, history, arguments and results

Contributor: Miller, Francis.|Shaw, Anna Howard 1847-1919|United States Congress. House. Committee on the Judiciary.|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: The Constitution, a title-deed to woman's franchise: a letter to Charles Sumner
Contributor: Tilton, Theodore 1835-1907|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This letter to Charles Sumner requests that he use his influence to urge the passage of legislation which would force New York to permit women to vote as guaranteed them by the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Amendments.
Publisher: Published at the Office of the Golden Age

Title: The history of equal suffrage in Colorado, 1868-1898
Contributor: Brown, J. G. (Joseph G.) 1844-|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Colorado women were enfranchised in 1898. This book details the history of that struggle. It includes a discussion of the growth of Colorado women's clubs as an important factor in the campaign. It also provides lists of suffrage workers and of women who have been elected and appointed to positions in Colorado government in the late nineteenth century.

Title: Equal suffrage: the results of an investigation in Colorado made for the Collegiate Equal Suffrage League of New York State
Contributor: Sumner, Helen L. (Helen Laura) 1876-1933|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: An examination of the effects of woman suffrage on "political and social life," using Colorado as a case study.

Title: Suffrage conferred by the Fourteenth Amendment: woman's suffrage in the Supreme Court of the District of Columbia, in general term, October, 1871 : Sara J. Spencer vs. The Board of Registration, and Sarah E. Webster vs. The Judges of Election : argument of the counsel for the plaintiffs : with the opinions of the court
Contributor: Riddle, A. G. (Albert Gallatin) 1816-1902|Miller, Francis active 1871-1874|Spencer, Sara J. (Sara Jane) 1837-1909|Webster, Sarah E.|Clephane, James O. (James Ogilvie) 1842-1910|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|District of Columbia Supreme Court (1863-1936)|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|Joseph Meredith Toner Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Sara J. Spencer and Sarah E. Webster each brought cases before the court in the District of Columbia arguing that they were enfranchised by the Fourteenth Amendment. This pamphlet contains the arguments of their lawyers in this regard and the decision of the supreme court of the District of Columbia, denying their claim.
Name subject: Spencer, Sara J. (Sara Jane) 1837-1909|Webster, Sarah E|United States. 14th Amendment.

Title: Report of the Woman's Rights Meeting, at Mercantile Hall, May 27, 1859
Contributor: Woman's Rights Meeting (1859 : Boston, Mass.)|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This is a report of a meeting held in Boston, Massachusetts, concerning women's rights in New England. Among the speakers were Wendell Phillips, Caroline Dall, Harriot Hunt, James Freeman Clarke, and John T. Sargent.

Title: Massachusetts in the woman suffrage movement: a general, political, legal and legislative history from 1774, to 1881
Contributor: Robinson, Harriet Jane Hanson 1825-1911|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Harriet Hanson was a Lowell mill operative in the 1830s and 1840s when she wrote "Loom and Spindle." In 1848, she married William Stevens Robinson, editor of the "Lowell courier." After the Civil War both Harriet and her husband became steadfast supporters of woman suffrage. This book by Robinson deals with the woman suffrage campaign in Massachusetts from 1774 to 1881. The writing is rather dry, but it includes a very good 88-page appendix containing a detailed description of the Lowell Mill; accounts of various attempts by women to gain limited access to voting rights; and statistical information on women's employment.

Title: Woman suffrage in New Jersey
Contributor: Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|New Jersey Legislature.|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: The woman voter's manual
Contributor: Forman, S. E. (Samuel Eagle) 1858-1941|Shuler, Marjorie|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: A good general explanation of American government. There are some interesting illustrations here summarizing legislation affecting women and children throughout the United States.
Extent: xviii, [8], 3-180 p. : front. (diagr.), illus., map ; 18 cm.

Contributor: United States Congress. House. Committee on the Judiciary.|Shaw, Anna Howard 1847-1919|United States Congress House. (57th, 1st session : 1901-1902).|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: The legal status of women
Contributor: Cassidy, Jessie J. (Jessie Jane) 1861-|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: In a series of seven chapters, Saunders undertakes an examination of the legal status of women in the United States concerning the property rights of married women -- including intestate estates and the right to support, divorce, child custody, rape and the age of consent, female criminality, and woman suffrage. Each chapter contains a brief overview, followed by a state-by state analysis of women's status. Also contains some interesting tables.

Title: Woman suffrage: the argument of Carrie S. Burnham before Chief Justice Reed, and Associate Justices Agnew, Sharswood and Mercur, of the Supreme Court of Pennsylvania, in banc, on the third and fourth of April, 1873 ; with an appendix containing the opinion of Hon. George Sharswood and a complete history of the case ; also, a compilation of the laws of  Pennsylvania touching the rights of women
Contributor: Burnham, Carrie S. (Carrie Sylvester) 1838-1909|Sharswood, George 1810-1883|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Carrie S. Burnham tried to vote in the state of Pennsylvania in 1871. This pamphlet concerns her arguments before the Supreme Court of Pennsylvania about why she was entitled to vote. In addition to Burnham's argument, it also contains the opinion of Justice Sharswood and a brief history of the laws of Pennsylvania regarding women. The case revolved around the use of the word "freemen," which, Burnham argued, applied to her; the court disagreed. Further, Sharswood argued that citizenship did not entitle one to the franchise; so, although women were citizens, their condition of citizenship did not automatically entitle them to vote.

Title: Woman suffrage by federal constitutional amendment
Contributor: Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This collection of essays focuses on the various arguments for and against woman suffrage by federal constitutional amendment rather than by individual states. An essay by Henry Wade Rogers provides an interesting counterpoint to another volume in this collection, "Woman's Suffrage by Constitutional Amendment," by Henry St. George Tucker [Section VII, no. 380].
Publisher: Published by National Woman Suffrage Publishing Co., Inc.

Title: Woman's suffrage by Constitutional amendment
Contributor: Tucker, Henry St. George 1853-1932|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This is a collection of lectures delivered by Tucker in the William Storrs Lecture Series, Yale University Law School, 1916, and originally titled "Local Self-Government." One lecture addresses the ways in which the proposal to enfranchise women by Constitutional amendment violates the "genius" of the Constitution. Good opposing arguments can be found in "Woman suffrage by federal Constitutional amendment" [Library, Carrie Chapman Catt, sec. VII, no. 60].

Title: Legal status of women in Iowa
Contributor: Wilson, Jennie L. (Jennie Lansley) 1847-|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Jennie Wilson was a member of the bar in Polk County, Iowa. In this book, she summarizes the legal status of women in such areas as marriage, divorce, property rights, apprenticeships of children, estates and wills, and rape.

Title: Address to the Legislature of New-York: adopted by the State Woman's Rights Convention, held at Albany, Tuesday and Wednesday, February 14 and 15, 1854
Contributor: Stanton, Elizabeth Cady 1815-1902|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|Susan B. Anthony Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: Memories of Jane Cunningham Croly, "Jenny June"
Contributor: Woman's Press Club of New York City|Croly, J. C. (Jane Cunningham) 1829-1901|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: Jane Cunningham Croly was the founder and president of the Women's Press Club of New York City (founded 1889) until her death in 1901. She was also the editor of "The Cycle," and a founding member and former president of Sorosis. This book includes various memorials offered at the time of Croly's death, as well as a collection of her own essays, speeches, and correspondence.
Extent: xi, 233 p. : 4 port. (incl. front.), 3 facsim. ; 21 cm.

Title: Women and the alphabet: a series of essays
Contributor: Higginson, Thomas Wentworth 1823-1911|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|Stone, Lucy 1818-1893|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)|Shapiro Bruce Rogers Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: Lucy Stone: a chronicle play
Contributor: Park, Maud Wood 1871-1955|Blackwell, Alice Stone 1857-1950|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)

Title: For rent -- one pedestal
Contributor: Shuler, Marjorie.|Catt, Carrie Chapman 1859-1947|National American Woman Suffrage Association Collection (Library of Congress)
Abstract: This is a series of letters between two fictional characters, Delight Dennison (an out-of-work teacher) and her friend, Barbara Martin. They are set in the community of Canton and document Dennison's transformation from anti-suffragism into an ardent worker for the woman suffrage campaign in her state. There are widespread references here to Canton and to political bossism and also some references to this being a western state. The letters document an unsuccessful state campaign and show how men supported the suffrage campaign.
Publisher: Published by National Woman Suffrage Publishing Co., Inc.
